> The chocolate mousse will take 2-3 hours to set so we'd recommend getting them prepared earlier in the day. However, they'll still be delicious if you only leave them in the fridge for less time. Make your pudding (all 3 steps) before you start cooking your main.

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Remove the @lamb steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them to come to room temperature. Trim and halve the @Chantenay carrots{150%g} lengthways (no need to peel). Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1} into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the @rosemary{½%bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop, discard the stalks. Pop the lamb into a large #bowl{} with the garlic, rosemary and @olive oil{1}(for the marinade), then mix until evenly coated. Set aside.

Halve the @salad potatoes{350%g} widthways and pop onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer, cut-side down. When the oven is hot, roast the potatoes on the top shelf, ~{20%minutes}. After ~, remove them from the oven. Use the bottom of a #bowl{} or pan to lightly crush each potato half. Drizzle the smashed potatoes with more oil and return to the top shelf until crispy and golden, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Once the smashed potatoes are back in the oven, heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Season the marinated lamb steaks with salt and pepper. When hot, lay them into the pan and fry until browned all over, ~{8-10%minutes} total (for medium-rare). Turn every ~{2%minutes}. Turn the heat down if needed.

> Cook for 2-3 mins extra if you like it more well done.

Once cooked, transfer to a #plate{} and leave to rest, covered loosely with #foil{}. Set the pan aside.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The lamb is cooked when browned on the outside.

Put a large #saucepan{} of water with 1/2 tsp salt on to boil for the veg. While the lamb rests, pop the (now empty) frying pan back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil. When hot, add the onion and stir-fry until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Once softened, pour in the @water{150%ml}(for the sauce). Bring to the boil, then stir in the @red wine jus paste{15%g}. Lower the heat slightly, then bubble away until reduced by half, ~{5-6%minutes}. Once glossy and thickened, remove from the heat.

Meanwhile, add the carrots to the pan of boiling water and cook for ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the @Tenderstem broccoli{150%g}, then cook the veg until just tender, ~{2-3%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back into the pan. Add the @unsalted butter{30%g}, season with salt and pepper then toss to coat.

Once everything is ready, thinly slice the lamb and transfer to your serving plates. Serve the smashed potatoes and veg alongside. Spoon over the red wine jus to finish. Enjoy!

== Chocolate Pot Dessert ==

Pour the @double cream{150%ml} into a medium saucepan and pop it on medium-high heat. Bring to the boil, then simmer for ~{1%minute}. Remove from the heat, then immediately add the @chocolate chips{100%g}. Allow to stand for ~{1%minute}, then stir together until smooth and well combined.

Pour the chocolate mixture into appropriately sized #glasses{} or #ramekins{}.

> TIP: Put these in the fridge beforehand to chill if you're in a rush - this will help the dessert to set.

Allow to cool completely, then cover with #cling film{} and pop into the fridge to set, ~{2-3%hours} minimum.

When you're ready to serve dessert, remove them from the fridge. Roughly chop the @pecan nut halves{25}(roughly chopped), then pop them into a small bowl. Pour over the @salted caramel sauce{40%g} and mix to combine. Spoon the salted caramel nuts on top of each chocolate pot and then serve.